# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: monad-transformers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] In functional programming, an **applicative functor**, or an applicative for short, is an intermediate structure between functors and monads.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Applicative functors allow for functorial computations to be sequenced (unlike plain functors), but don't allow using results from prior computations in the definition of subsequent ones (unlike monads).
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] In terms of category theory, applicative functors may be defined as lax monoidal functors with tensorial strength.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] This may not be the most obvious categorification of the standard definition of applicative functor given below, but they are equivalent in the category of Haskell types.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Note that the observation that all monads are applicative functors is specific to the category of Haskell types, and is not true in general with this categorical definition of applicative functor; monads in an arbitrary category need not preserve any monoidal product.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Applicative functors were introduced in 2008 by Conor McBride and Ross Paterson in their paper *Applicative programming with effects*.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Applicative functors first appeared as a library feature in Haskell, but have since spread to other languages such as Idris, Agda, OCaml, Scala, and F#.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Glasgow Haskell, Idris, and F# offer language features designed to ease programming with applicative functors.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] In Haskell, applicative functors are implemented in the `Applicative` type class.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] While in languages like Haskell monads are applicative functors, this is not always the case in general settings of category theory—examples of monads which are *not* strong can be found on Math Overflow.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] In Haskell, an applicative is a parameterized type that can be thought of as being a container for data of the parameter type with two additional methods: `pure` and `<*>`.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] and can be thought of as bringing values into the applicative.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] and can be thought of as the equivalent of function application inside the applicative.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Alternatively, instead of providing `<*>`, one may provide a function called `liftA2`.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] These two functions may be defined in terms of each other; therefore only one is needed for a minimally complete definition.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] The commonly used notation `g <$> x` is equivalent to `pure g <*> x`.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] As stated in the Definition section, `pure` turns an `a` into a `Maybe a`, and `<*>` applies a Maybe function to a Maybe value.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] Using the Maybe applicative for type `a` allows one to operate on values of type `a` with the error being handled automatically by the applicative machinery.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] For the non-error case, adding `m=Just i` and `n=Just j` gives `Just(i+j)`.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] If either of `m` or `n` is `Nothing`, then the result will be `Nothing` also.
[src:monad-transformers/applicative-functor] This example also demonstrates how applicatives allow a sort of generalized function application.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] In functional programming, a **functor** is a design pattern inspired by the definition from category theory that allows one to apply a function to values inside a generic type without changing the structure of the generic type.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] This declaration says that any instance of `Functor` must support a method `fmap`, which maps a function over the elements of the instance.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] where `.` stands for function composition.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] Functors form a base for more complex abstractions like applicative functors, monads, and comonads, all of which build atop a canonical functor structure.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] Functors are useful in modeling functional effects by values of parameterized data types.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] Modifiable computations are modeled by allowing a pure function to be applied to values of the "inner" type, thus creating the new overall value which represents the modified computation (which may have yet to run).
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] In Haskell, lists are a simple example of a functor.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] If we have a binary tree `tr :: Tree a` and a function `f :: a -> b`, the function `fmap f tr` will apply `f` to every element of `tr`.
[src:monad-transformers/functor-functional-programming] For example, if `a` is `Int`, adding 1 to each element of `tr` can be expressed as `fmap (+ 1) tr`.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] In category theory, a **Kleisli category** is a category naturally associated to any monad *T*.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] It is equivalent to the category of free *T*-algebras.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] The Kleisli category is one of two extremal solutions to the question: "*Does every monad arise from an adjunction?*" The other extremal solution is the Eilenberg–Moore category.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Kleisli categories are named for the mathematician Heinrich Kleisli.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Let ⟨*T*, *η*, *μ*⟩ be a monad over a category *C*.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] That is, every morphism *f: X → T Y* in *C* (with codomain *TY*) can also be regarded as a morphism in *C**T* (but with codomain *Y*).
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] An alternative way of writing this, which clarifies the category in which each object lives, is used by MacLane.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] We use very slightly different notation for this presentation.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Given the same monad and category C as above, we associate with each object X in C a new object $X_{T}$ , and for each morphism $f\colon X\to TY$ in C a morphism $f^{*}\colon X_{T}\to Y_{T}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Composition of Kleisli arrows can be expressed succinctly by means of the *extension operator* (–)# : Hom(*X*, *TY*) → Hom(*TX*, *TY*).
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] It follows trivially from these properties that Kleisli composition is associative and that *η**X* is the identity.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] In fact, to give a monad is to give a *Kleisli triple* ⟨*T*, *η*, (–)#⟩, i.e.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] such that the above three equations for extension operators are satisfied.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Kleisli categories were originally defined in order to show that every monad arises from an adjunction.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Let ⟨*T*, *η*, *μ*⟩ be a monad over a category *C* and let *C**T* be the associated Kleisli category.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] One can show that *F* and *G* are indeed functors and that *F* is left adjoint to *G*.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Finally, one can show that *T* = *GF* and *μ* = *GεF* so that ⟨*T*, *η*, *μ*⟩ is the monad associated to the adjunction ⟨*F*, *G*, *η*, *ε*⟩.
[src:monad-transformers/kleisli-category] Since $(G\circ F)(X)=TX$ is true for any object *X* in *C* and $(G\circ F)(f)=Tf$ is true for any morphism *f* in *C*, then $G\circ F=T$ .
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In functional programming, **monads** are a way to structure computations as a sequence of steps, where each step not only produces a value but also some extra information about the computation, such as a potential failure, non-determinism, or side effect.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] More formally, a monad is a type constructor M equipped with two operations, `return : <A>(a : A) -> M(A)` which lifts a value into the monadic context, and `bind : <A,B>(m_a : M(A), f : A -> M(B)) -> M(B)` which chains monadic computations.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In simpler terms, monads can be thought of as interfaces implemented on type constructors, that allow for functions to abstract over various type constructor variants that implement monad (e.g.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Both the concept of a monad and the term originally come from category theory, where a monad is defined as an endofunctor with additional structure.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Research beginning in the late 1980s and early 1990s established that monads could bring seemingly disparate computer-science problems under a unified, functional model.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Category theory also provides a few formal requirements, known as the **monad laws**, which should be satisfied by any monad and can be used to verify monadic code.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Since monads make semantics explicit for a kind of computation, they can also be used to implement convenient language features.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Some languages, such as Haskell, even offer pre-built definitions in their core libraries for the general monad structure and common instances.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] "For a monad `m`, a value of type `m a` represents having access to a value of type `a` within the context of the monad." —C.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] More exactly, a monad can be used where unrestricted access to a value is inappropriate for reasons specific to the scenario.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In the case of the Maybe monad, it is because the value may not exist.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In the case of the IO monad, it is because the value may not be known yet, such as when the monad represents user input that will only be provided after a prompt is displayed.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In all cases the scenarios in which access makes sense are captured by the bind operation defined for the monad; for the Maybe monad a value is bound only if it exists, and for the IO monad a value is bound only after the previous operations in the sequence have been performed.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] With these elements, the programmer composes a sequence of function calls (a "pipeline") with several *bind* operators chained together in an expression.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Each function call transforms its input plain-type value, and the bind operator handles the returned monadic value, which is fed into the next step in the sequence.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Typically, the bind operator `>>=` may contain code unique to the monad that performs additional computation steps not available in the function received as a parameter.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Between each pair of composed function calls, the bind operator can inject into the monadic value `m a` some additional information that is not accessible within the function `f`, and pass it along down the pipeline.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] It can also exert finer control of the flow of execution, for example by calling the function only under some conditions, or executing the function calls in a particular order.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] One example of a monad is the `Maybe` type.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Undefined null results are one particular pain point that many procedural languages don't provide specific tools for dealing with, requiring use of the null object pattern or checks to test for invalid values at each operation to handle undefined values.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This causes bugs and makes it harder to build robust software that gracefully handles errors.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The `Maybe` type forces the programmer to deal with these potentially undefined results by explicitly defining the two states of a result: `Just ⌑result⌑`, or `Nothing`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] For example, the programmer might be constructing a parser, which is to return an intermediate result, or else signal a condition which the parser has detected, and which the programmer must also handle.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] With just a little extra functional spice on top, this `Maybe` type transforms into a fully-featured monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In most languages, the Maybe monad is also known as an option type, which is just a type that marks whether or not it contains a value.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Typically they are expressed as some kind of enumerated type.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In the Rust programming language it is called `Option<T>` and variants of this type can either be a value of generic type `T`, or the empty variant: `None`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `Option<T>` can also be understood as a "wrapping" type, and this is where its connection to monads comes in.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In languages with some form of the Maybe type, there are functions that aid in their use such as composing **monadic functions** with each other and testing if a Maybe contains a value.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In the following hard-coded example, a Maybe type is used as a result of functions that may fail, in this case the type returns nothing if there is a divide-by-zero.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] One such way to test whether or not a Maybe contains a value is to use `if` statements.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Monads can compose functions that return Maybe, putting them together.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Instead of repeating `Some` expressions, we can use something called a *bind* operator.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] (also known as "map", "flatmap", or "shove").
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This operation takes a monad and a function that returns a monad and runs the function on the inner value of the passed monad, returning the monad from the function.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In Haskell, there is an operator *bind*, or (`>>=`) that allows for this monadic composition in a more elegant form similar to function composition.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] With `>>=` available, `chainable_division` can be expressed much more succinctly with the help of anonymous functions (i.e. lambdas).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Notice in the expression below how the two nested lambdas each operate on the wrapped value in the passed `Maybe` monad using the bind operator.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] What has been shown so far is basically a monad, but to be more concise, the following is a strict list of qualities necessary for a monad as defined by the following section.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] These are the 3 things necessary to form a monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Other monads may embody different logical processes, and some may have additional properties, but all of them will have these three similar components.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The more common definition for a monad in functional programming, used in the above example, is actually based on a Kleisli triple ⟨T, η, μ⟩ rather than category theory's standard definition.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The two constructs turn out to be mathematically equivalent, however, so either definition will yield a valid monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Algebraically, this means any monad both gives rise to a category (called the Kleisli category) *and* a monoid in the category of functors (from values to computations), with monadic composition as a binary operator in the monoid and unit as identity in the monoid.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The value of the monad pattern goes beyond merely condensing code and providing a link to mathematical reasoning.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Whatever language or default programming paradigm a developer uses, following the monad pattern brings many of the benefits of purely functional programming.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] By reifying a specific kind of computation, a monad not only encapsulates the tedious details of that computational pattern, but it does so in a declarative way, improving the code's clarity.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] As monadic values explicitly represent not only computed values, but computed *effects*, a monadic expression can be replaced with its value in referentially transparent positions, much like pure expressions can be, allowing for many techniques and optimizations based on rewriting.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Typically, programmers will use bind to chain monadic functions into a sequence, which has led some to describe monads as "programmable semicolons", a reference to how many imperative languages use semicolons to separate statements.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] However, monads do not actually order computations; even in languages that use them as central features, simpler function composition can arrange steps within a program.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A monad's general utility rather lies in simplifying a program's structure and improving separation of concerns through abstraction.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The monad structure can also be seen as a uniquely mathematical and compile time variation on the decorator pattern.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Some monads can pass along extra data that is inaccessible to functions, and some even exert finer control over execution, for example only calling a function under certain conditions.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Because they let application programmers implement domain logic while offloading boilerplate code onto pre-developed modules, monads can even be considered a tool for aspect-oriented programming.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] One other noteworthy use for monads is isolating side-effects, like input/output or mutable state, in otherwise purely functional code.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Even purely functional languages *can* still implement these "impure" computations without monads, via an intricate mix of function composition and continuation-passing style (CPS) in particular.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] With monads though, much of this scaffolding can be abstracted away, essentially by taking each recurring pattern in CPS code and bundling it into a distinct monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] If a language does not support monads by default, it is still possible to implement the pattern, often without much difficulty.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] When translated from category-theory to programming terms, the monad structure is a generic concept and can be defined directly in any language that supports an equivalent feature for bounded polymorphism.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A concept's ability to remain agnostic about operational details while working on underlying types is powerful, but the unique features and stringent behavior of monads set them apart from other concepts.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Discussions of specific monads will typically focus on solving a narrow implementation problem since a given monad represents a specific computational form.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In some situations though, an application can even meet its high-level goals by using appropriate monads within its core logic.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The term "monad" in programming dates to the APL and J programming languages, which do tend toward being purely functional.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] However, in those languages, "monad" is only shorthand for a function taking one parameter (a function with two parameters being a "dyad", and so on).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The mathematician Roger Godement was the first to formulate the concept of a monad (dubbing it a "standard construction") in the late 1950s, though the term "monad" that came to dominate was popularized by category-theorist Saunders Mac Lane.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The form defined above using bind, however, was originally described in 1965 by mathematician Heinrich Kleisli in order to prove that any monad could be characterized as an adjunction between two (covariant) functors.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Starting in the 1980s, a vague notion of the monad pattern began to surface in the computer science community.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] According to programming language researcher Philip Wadler, computer scientist John C.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Reynolds anticipated several facets of it in the 1970s and early 1980s, when he discussed the value of continuation-passing style, of category theory as a rich source for formal semantics, and of the type distinction between values and computations.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The research language Opal, which was actively designed up until 1990, also effectively based I/O on a monadic type, but the connection was not realized at the time.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The computer scientist Eugenio Moggi was the first to explicitly link the monad of category theory to functional programming, in a conference paper in 1989, followed by a more refined journal submission in 1991.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In earlier work, several computer scientists had advanced using category theory to provide semantics for the lambda calculus.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Moggi's key insight was that a real-world program is not just a function from values to other values, but rather a transformation that forms *computations* on those values.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] When formalized in category-theoretic terms, this leads to the conclusion that monads are the structure to represent these computations.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Several others popularized and built on this idea, including Philip Wadler and Simon Peyton Jones, both of whom were involved in the specification of Haskell.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In particular, Haskell used a problematic "lazy stream" model up through v1.2 to reconcile I/O with lazy evaluation, until switching over to a more flexible monadic interface.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The Haskell community would go on to apply monads to many problems in functional programming, and in the 2010s, researchers working with Haskell eventually recognized that monads are applicative functors; and that both monads and arrows are monoids.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] At first, programming with monads was largely confined to Haskell and its derivatives, but as functional programming has influenced other paradigms, many languages have incorporated a monad pattern (in spirit if not in name).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Formulations now exist in Scheme, Perl, Python, Racket, Clojure, Scala, F#, and have also been considered for a new ML standard.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] One benefit of the monad pattern is bringing mathematical precision on the composition of computations.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Not only can the monad laws be used to check an instance's validity, but features from related structures (like functors) can be used through subtyping.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Returning to the `Maybe` example, its components were declared to make up a monad, but no proof was given that it satisfies the monad laws.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Though rarer in computer science, one can use category theory directly, which defines a monad as a functor with two additional natural transformations.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This is not always a major issue, however, especially when a monad is derived from a pre-existing functor, whereupon the monad inherits map automatically.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A monad's first transformation is actually the same unit from the Kleisli triple, but following the hierarchy of structures closely, it turns out unit characterizes an applicative functor, an intermediate structure between a monad and a basic functor.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In the applicative context, unit is sometimes referred to as **pure** but is still the same function.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The **List monad** naturally demonstrates how deriving a monad from a simpler functor can come in handy.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In many languages, a list structure comes pre-defined along with some basic features, so a `List` type constructor and append operator (represented with `++` for infix notation) are assumed as already given here.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] From here, applying a function iteratively with a list comprehension may seem like an easy choice for bind and converting lists to a full monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The difficulty with this approach is that bind expects monadic functions, which in this case will output lists themselves; as more functions are applied, layers of nested lists will accumulate, requiring more than a basic comprehension.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Now, these two procedures already promote `List` to an applicative functor.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] One application for this monadic list is representing nondeterministic computation.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `List` can hold results for all execution paths in an algorithm, then condense itself at each step to "forget" which paths led to which results (a sometimes important distinction from deterministic, exhaustive algorithms).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Another benefit is that checks can be embedded in the monad; specific paths can be pruned transparently at their first point of failure, with no need to rewrite functions in the pipeline.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A second situation where `List` shines is composing multivalued functions.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] For instance, the nth complex root of a number should yield n distinct complex numbers, but if another mth root is then taken of those results, the final m•n values should be identical to the output of the m•nth root.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `List` completely automates this issue away, condensing the results from each step into a flat, mathematically correct list.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Monads present opportunities for interesting techniques beyond just organizing program logic.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Monads can lay the groundwork for useful syntactic features while their high-level and mathematical nature enable significant abstraction.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Although using bind openly often makes sense, many programmers prefer a syntax that mimics imperative statements (called *do-notation* in Haskell, *perform-notation* in OCaml, *computation expressions* in F#, and *for comprehension* in Scala).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This is only syntactic sugar that disguises a monadic pipeline as a code block; the compiler will then quietly translate these expressions into underlying functional code.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Translating the `add` function from the `Maybe` into Haskell can show this feature in action.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A second example shows how `Maybe` can be used in an entirely different language: F#.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Every monad needs a specific implementation that meets the monad laws, but other aspects like the relation to other structures or standard idioms within a language are shared by all monads.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] As a result, a language or library may provide a general `Monad` interface with function prototypes, subtyping relationships, and other general facts.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Besides providing a head-start to development and guaranteeing a new monad inherits features from a supertype (such as functors), checking a monad's design against the interface adds another layer of quality control.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Monadic code can often be simplified even further through the judicious use of operators.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The map functional can be especially helpful since it works on more than just ad-hoc monadic functions; so long as a monadic function should work analogously to a predefined operator, map can be used to instantly "lift" the simpler operator into a monadic one.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The process could be taken even one step further by defining `add` not just for `Maybe`, but for the whole `Monad` interface.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] By doing this, any new monad that matches the structure interface and implements its own map will immediately inherit a lifted version of `add` too.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `Identity` does actually have valid uses though, such as providing a base case for recursive monad transformers.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] It can also be used to perform basic variable assignment within an imperative-style block.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Any collection with a proper append is already a monoid, but it turns out that `List` is not the only collection that also has a well-defined join and qualifies as a monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] As already mentioned, pure code should not have unmanaged side effects, but that does not preclude a program from *explicitly* describing and managing effects.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This idea is central to Haskell's **IO monad**, where an object of type `IO a` can be seen as describing an action to be performed in the world, optionally providing information about the world of type `a`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] An action that provides no information about the world has the type `IO ()`, "providing" the dummy value `()`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] When a programmer binds an `IO` value to a function, the function computes the next action to be performed based on the information about the world provided by the previous action (input from users, files, etc.).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Most significantly, because the value of the IO monad can only be bound to a function that computes another IO monad, the bind function imposes a discipline of a sequence of actions where the result of an action can only be provided to a function that will compute the next action to perform.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This means that actions which do not need to be performed never are, and actions that do need to be performed have a well defined sequence.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] For example, Haskell has several functions for acting on the wider file system, including one that checks whether a file exists and another that deletes a file.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The first is interested in whether a given file really exists, and as a result, outputs a Boolean value within the `IO` monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The second function, on the other hand, is only concerned with acting on the file system so the `IO` container it outputs is empty.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Another common situation is keeping a log file or otherwise reporting a program's progress.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes, a programmer may want to log even more specific, technical data for later profiling or debugging.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The **Writer monad** can handle these tasks by generating auxiliary output that accumulates step-by-step.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] To show how the monad pattern is not restricted to primarily functional languages, this example implements a `Writer` monad in Java, stored in a class representing the `Writer` monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] An environment monad (also called a *reader monad* and a *function monad*) allows a computation to depend on values from a shared environment.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The monad type constructor maps a type T to functions of type *E* → *T*, where E is the type of the shared environment.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The ask operation is used to retrieve the current context, while local executes a computation in a modified subcontext.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] As in a state monad, computations in the environment monad may be invoked by simply providing an environment value and applying it to an instance of the monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Formally, a value in an environment monad is equivalent to a function with an additional, anonymous argument; return and bind are equivalent to the K and S combinators, respectively, in the SKI combinator calculus.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A state monad allows a programmer to attach state information of any type to a calculation.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Given any value type, the corresponding type in the state monad is a function which accepts a state, then outputs a new state (of type `s`) along with a return value (of type `t`).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This is similar to an environment monad, except that it also returns a new state, and thus allows modeling a *mutable* environment.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Note that this monad takes a type parameter, the type of the state information.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] do-blocks in a state monad are sequences of operations that can examine and update the state data.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Informally, a state monad of state type S maps the type of return values T into functions of type $S\rightarrow T\times S$ , where S is the underlying state.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] From the category theory point of view, a state monad is derived from the adjunction between the product functor and the exponential functor, which exists in any cartesian closed category by definition.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A continuation monad with return type R maps type T into functions of type $\left(T\rightarrow R\right)\rightarrow R$ .
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] It is used to model continuation-passing style.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] That is, both functions take in an integer and return another integer.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Where the result is the result of `foo` applied to the result of `bar` applied to `x`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] But suppose we are debugging our program, and we would like to add logging messages to `foo` and `bar`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] So that both functions return a tuple, with the result of the application as the integer, and a logging message with information about the applied function and all the previously applied functions as the string.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Unfortunately, this means we can no longer compose `foo` and `bar`, as their input type `int` is not compatible with their output type `int * string`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] And although we can again gain composability by modifying the types of each function to be `int * string -> int * string`, this would require us to add boilerplate code to each function to extract the integer from the tuple, which would get tedious as the number of such functions increases.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `bind` takes in an integer and string tuple, then takes in a function (like `foo`) that maps from an integer to an integer and string tuple.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Its output is an integer and string tuple, which is the result of applying the input function to the integer within the input integer and string tuple.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In this way, we only need to write boilerplate code to extract the integer from the tuple once, in `bind`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Now we have regained some composability.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Where `(x,s)` is an integer and string tuple.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] So that `t >>= f` is the same as `bind t f`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Finally, we define a new function to avoid writing `(x, "")` every time we wish to create an empty logging message, where `""` is the empty string.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Which wraps `x` in the tuple described above.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] That allows us to more easily log the effects of `bar` and `foo` on `x`.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `int * string` denotes a pseudo-coded **monadic value**.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `bind` and `return` are analogous to the corresponding functions of the same name.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In fact, `int * string`, `bind`, and `return` form a monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] An **additive monad** is a monad endowed with an additional closed, associative, binary operator **mplus** and an identity element under mplus, called **mzero**.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The `Maybe` monad can be considered additive, with `Nothing` as mzero and a variation on the OR operator as mplus.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `List` is also an additive monad, with the empty list `[]` acting as mzero and the concatenation operator `++` as mplus.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Intuitively, mzero represents a monadic wrapper with no value from an underlying type, but is also considered a "zero" (rather than a "one") since it acts as an absorber for bind, returning mzero whenever bound to a monadic function.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This property is two-sided, and bind will also return mzero when any value is bound to a monadic zero function.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In category-theoretic terms, an additive monad qualifies once as a monoid over monadic functions with bind (as all monads do), and again over monadic values via mplus.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes, the general outline of a monad may be useful, but no simple pattern recommends one monad or another.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] This is where a **free monad** comes in; as a free object in the category of monads, it can represent monadic structure without any specific constraints beyond the monad laws themselves.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Just as a free monoid concatenates elements without evaluation, a free monad allows chaining computations with markers to satisfy the type system, but otherwise imposes no deeper semantics itself.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] For example, by working entirely through the `Just` and `Nothing` markers, the `Maybe` monad is in fact a free monad.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] The `List` monad, on the other hand, is not a free monad since it brings extra, specific facts about lists (like append) into its definition.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Free monads, however, are *not* restricted to a linked-list like in this example, and can be built around other structures like trees.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Using free monads intentionally may seem impractical at first, but their formal nature is particularly well-suited for syntactic problems.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A free monad can be used to track syntax and type while leaving semantics for later, and has found use in parsers and interpreters as a result.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Others have applied them to more dynamic, operational problems too, such as providing iteratees within a language.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Besides generating monads with extra properties, for any given monad, one can also define a **comonad**.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Conceptually, if monads represent computations built up from underlying values, then comonads can be seen as reductions back down to values.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Monadic code, in a sense, cannot be fully "unpacked"; once a value is wrapped within a monad, it remains quarantined there along with any side-effects (a good thing in purely functional programming).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Sometimes though, a problem is more about consuming contextual data, which comonads can model explicitly.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Technically, a comonad is the categorical dual of a monad, which loosely means that it will have the same required components, only with the direction of the type signatures *reversed*.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] While operations like extend are reversed, however, a comonad does *not* reverse functions it acts on, and consequently, comonads are still functors with map, not cofunctors.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A simple example is the **Product comonad**, which outputs values based on an input value and shared environment data.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In fact, the `Product` comonad is just the dual of the `Writer` monad and effectively the same as the `Reader` monad (both discussed below).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] `Product` and `Reader` differ only in which function signatures they accept, and how they complement those functions by wrapping or unwrapping values.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] A less trivial example is the **Stream comonad**, which can be used to represent data streams and attach filters to the incoming signals with extend.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] In fact, while not as popular as monads, researchers have found comonads particularly useful for stream processing and modeling dataflow programming.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] Due to their strict definitions, however, one cannot simply move objects back and forth between monads and comonads.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-functional-programming] As an even higher abstraction, arrows can subsume both structures, but finding more granular ways to combine monadic and comonadic code is an active area of research.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-transformer] In functional programming, a **monad transformer** is a type constructor which takes a monad as an argument and returns a monad as a result.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-transformer] Monad transformers can be used to compose features encapsulated by monads – such as state, exception handling, and I/O – in a modular way.
[src:monad-transformers/monad-transformer] Typically, a monad transformer is created by generalising an existing monad; applying the resulting monad transformer to the identity monad yields a monad which is equivalent to the original monad (ignoring any necessary boxing and unboxing).
[src:monad-transformers/monad-transformer] Given any monad $\mathrm {M} \,A$ , the continuation monad transformer maps an arbitrary type R into functions of type $(A\rightarrow \mathrm {M} \,R)\rightarrow \mathrm {M} \,R$ , where R is the result type of the continuation.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a **natural transformation** provides a way of transforming one functor into another while respecting the internal structure (i.e., the composition of morphisms) of the categories involved.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Hence, a natural transformation can be considered to be a "morphism of functors".
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Informally, the notion of a natural transformation states that a particular map between functors can be done consistently over an entire category.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Indeed, this intuition can be formalized to define so-called functor categories.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Natural transformations are, after categories and functors, one of the most fundamental notions of category theory and consequently appear in the majority of its applications.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If F and G are functors between the categories ${\mathcal {C}}$ and ${\mathcal {D}}$ (both from ${\mathcal {C}}$ to ${\mathcal {D}}$ ), then a **natural transformation** $\eta$ from F to G is a family of morphisms $(\eta _{X})_{X\in {\text{ob}}({\mathcal {C}})}$ , where $\eta _{X}:F(X)\to G(X)$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If both F and G are instead contravariant functors, the vertical arrows in the right diagram are reversed.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If $\eta$ is a natural transformation from F to G , we also write $\eta :F\to G$ or $\eta :F\Rightarrow G$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This is also expressed by saying the family of morphisms $\eta _{X}:F(X)\to G(X)$ is **natural** in X .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If, for every object X in ${\mathcal {C}}$ , the morphism $\eta _{X}$ is an isomorphism in ${\mathcal {D}}$ , then $\eta$ is said to be a **natural isomorphism** (or sometimes **natural equivalence** or **isomorphism of functors**).
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Two functors F and G are called *naturally isomorphic* or simply *isomorphic* if there exists a natural isomorphism from F to G in their category.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] An **infranatural transformation** $\eta :F\Rightarrow G$ is simply the family of components for all X in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Thus, a natural transformation is a special case of an infranatural transformation for which $\eta _{Y}\circ F(f)=G(f)\circ \eta _{X}$ for every morphism $f:X\to Y$ in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The **naturalizer** of $\eta$ , $\operatorname {nat} (\eta )$ , is the largest subcategory ${\mathcal {C}}_{S}\subseteq {\mathcal {C}}$ (S for subcategory) containing all the objects of ${\mathcal {C}}$ on which $\eta$ restricts to a natural transformation.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Alternatively put, $\operatorname {nat} (\eta )$ is the largest ${\mathcal {C}}_{S}\subseteq {\mathcal {C}}$ such that ${\displaystyle \,\eta |_{{\mathcal {C}}_{S}}\$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] We will now give the precise meaning of this statement as well as its proof.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Consider the category ${\textbf {Grp}}$ of all groups with group homomorphisms as morphisms.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If $(G,*)$ is a group, we define its opposite group $(G^{\text{op}},{*}^{\text{op}})$ as follows: $G^{\text{op}}$ is the same set as G , and the operation $*^{\text{op}}$ is defined by $a*^{\text{op}}b=b*a$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] All multiplications in $G^{\text{op}}$ are thus "turned around".
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Forming the opposite group becomes a (covariant) functor from ${\textbf {Grp}}$ to ${\textbf {Grp}}$ if we define $f^{\text{op}}=f$ for any group homomorphism $f:G\to H$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] To prove this, we need to provide isomorphisms $\eta _{G}:G\to G^{\text{op}}$ for every group G , such that the above diagram commutes.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This is true since $f^{\text{op}}=f$ and every group homomorphism has the property $(f(a))^{-1}=f(a^{-1})$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Given a group G , we can define its abelianization $G^{\text{ab}}=G/[G,G]$ , where $[G,G]$ denotes the commutator subgroup of G .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Let $\pi _{G}:G\to G^{\text{ab}}$ denote the projection map onto the cosets of $[G,G]$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This homomorphism is "natural in G ", i.e., it defines a natural transformation, which we now check.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] For any homomorphism $f:G\to H$ , we have that $[G,G]$ is contained in the kernel of $\pi _{H}\circ f$ , because any homomorphism into an abelian group kills the commutator subgroup.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This makes ${\text{ab}}:{\textbf {Grp}}\to {\textbf {Grp}}$ a functor and $\pi$ a natural transformation, but not a natural isomorphism, from the identity functor to ${\text{ab}}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Functors and natural transformations abound in algebraic topology, with the Hurewicz homomorphisms serving as examples.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] from the n -th homotopy group of $(X,x)$ to the n -th homology group of X .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Both $\pi _{n}$ and $H_{n}$ are functors from the category **Top*** of pointed topological spaces to the category **Grp** of groups, and $h_{n}$ is a natural transformation from $\pi _{n}$ to $H_{n}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Given commutative rings R and S with a ring homomorphism $f:R\to S$ , the respective groups of invertible $n\times n$ matrices ${\text{GL}}_{n}(R)$ and ${\text{GL}}_{n}(S)$ inherit a homomorphism which we denote by ${\text{GL}}_{n}(f)$ , obtained by applying f to each matrix entry.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Similarly, f restricts to a group homomorphism $f^{*}:R^{*}\to S^{*}$ , where $R^{*}$ denotes the group of units of R .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] In fact, ${\text{GL}}_{n}$ and * are functors from the category of commutative rings ${\textbf {CRing}}$ to ${\textbf {Grp}}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] which is natural in R : because the determinant is defined by the same formula for every ring, $f^{*}\circ {\text{det}}_{R}={\text{det}}_{S}\circ {\text{GL}}_{n}(f)$ holds.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This makes the determinant a natural transformation from ${\text{GL}}_{n}$ to * .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If K is a field, then for every vector space V over K we have a "natural" injective linear map $V\to V^{**}$ from the vector space into its double dual.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] These maps are "natural" in the following sense: the double dual operation is a functor, and the maps are the components of a natural transformation from the identity functor to the double dual functor.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] For every abelian group G , the set ${\text{Hom}}_{\textbf {Set}}(\mathbb {Z} ,U(G))$ of functions from the integers to the underlying set of G forms an abelian group $V_{\mathbb {Z} }(G)$ under pointwise addition.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The finite difference operator $\Delta _{G}$ taking each function $f:\mathbb {Z} \to U(G)$ to $\Delta (f):n\mapsto f(n+1)-f(n)$ is a map from $V_{\mathbb {Z} }(G)$ to itself, and the collection $\Delta$ of such maps gives a natural transformation $\Delta :V_{\mathbb {Z} }\to V_{\mathbb {Z} }$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Let $\varphi :M\longrightarrow M^{\prime }$ be an R -module homomorphism of right modules.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] For every left module N there is a natural map $\varphi \otimes N:M\otimes _{R}N\longrightarrow M^{\prime }\otimes _{R}N$ , form a natural transformation $\eta :M\otimes _{R}-\implies M'\otimes _{R}-$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] For every right module N there is a natural map $\eta _{N}:{\text{Hom}}_{R}(M',N)\longrightarrow {\text{Hom}}_{R}(M,N)$ defined by $\eta _{N}(f)=f\varphi$ , form a natural transformation ${\displaystyle \eta$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Consider the category ${\textbf {Ab}}$ of abelian groups and group homomorphisms.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] These isomorphisms are "natural" in the sense that they define a natural transformation between the two involved functors ${\textbf {Ab}}^{\text{op}}\times {\textbf {Ab}}^{\text{op}}\times {\textbf {Ab}}\to {\textbf {Ab}}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This is formally the tensor-hom adjunction, and is an archetypal example of a pair of adjoint functors.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Natural transformations arise frequently in conjunction with adjoint functors, and indeed, adjoint functors are defined by a certain natural isomorphism.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Additionally, every pair of adjoint functors comes equipped with two natural transformations (generally not isomorphisms) called the *unit* and *counit*.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The notion of a natural transformation is categorical, and states (informally) that a particular map between functors can be done consistently over an entire category.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Conversely, a particular map between particular objects may be called an **unnatural isomorphism** (or "an isomorphism that is not natural") if the map cannot be extended to a natural transformation on the entire category.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The maps of the category play a crucial role – any infranatural transform is natural if the only maps are the identity map, for instance.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Some authors distinguish notationally, using $\cong$ for a natural isomorphism and $\approx$ for an unnatural isomorphism, reserving = for equality (usually equality of maps).
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Every finite-dimensional vector space is isomorphic to its dual space, but there may be many different isomorphisms between the two spaces.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] There is in general no natural isomorphism between a finite-dimensional vector space and its dual space.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] However, related categories (with additional structure and restrictions on the maps) do have a natural isomorphism, as described below.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The dual space of a finite-dimensional vector space is again a finite-dimensional vector space of the same dimension, and these are thus isomorphic, since dimension is the only invariant of finite-dimensional vector spaces over a given field.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] However, in the absence of additional constraints (such as a requirement that maps preserve the chosen basis), the map from a space to its dual is not unique, and thus such an isomorphism requires a choice, and is "not natural".
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Intuitively this is because it required a choice, rigorously because *any* such choice of isomorphisms will not commute with, say, the zero map; see (Mac Lane & Birkhoff 1999, §VI.4) for detailed discussion.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Starting from finite-dimensional vector spaces (as objects) and the identity and dual functors, one can define a natural isomorphism, but this requires first adding additional structure, then restricting the maps from "all linear maps" to "linear maps that respect this structure".
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Explicitly, for each vector space, require that it comes with the data of an isomorphism to its dual, $\eta _{V}\colon V\to V^{*}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] In other words, take as objects vector spaces with a nondegenerate bilinear form $b_{V}\colon V\times V\to K$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This defines an infranatural isomorphism (isomorphism for each object).
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] One then restricts the maps to only those maps $T\colon V\to U$ that commute with the isomorphisms: $T^{*}(\eta _{U}(T(v)))=\eta _{V}(v)$ or in other words, preserve the bilinear form: $b_{U}(T(v),T(w))=b_{V}(v,w)$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Viewed in this light, this construction (add transforms for each object, restrict maps to commute with these) is completely general, and does not depend on any particular properties of vector spaces.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] In this category (finite-dimensional vector spaces with a nondegenerate bilinear form, maps linear transforms that respect the bilinear form), the dual of a map between vector spaces can be identified as a transpose.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If $\eta :F\Rightarrow G$ and $\epsilon :G\Rightarrow H$ are natural transformations between functors $F,G,H:C\to D$ , then we can compose them to get a natural transformation $\epsilon \circ \eta :F\Rightarrow H$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This vertical composition of natural transformations is associative and has an identity, and allows one to consider the collection of all functors $C\to D$ itself as a category (see below under Functor categories).
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The identity natural transformation $\mathrm {id} _{F}$ on functor F has components $(\mathrm {id} _{F})_{X}=\mathrm {id} _{F(X)}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This horizontal composition of natural transformations is also associative with identity.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This identity is the identity natural transformation on the identity functor, i.e., the natural transformation that associate to each object its identity morphism: for object X in category C , $(\mathrm {id} _{\mathrm {id} _{C}})_{X}=\mathrm {id} _{\mathrm {id} _{C}(X)}=\mathrm {id} _{X}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] As identity functors $\mathrm {id} _{C}$ and $\mathrm {id} _{D}$ are functors, the identity for horizontal composition is also the identity for vertical composition, but not vice versa.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Whiskering is an external binary operation between a functor and a natural transformation.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Note that $\mathrm {id} _{H}$ (resp. $\mathrm {id} _{K}$ ) is generally not the left (resp. right) identity of horizontal composition * ( $H\eta \neq \eta$ and $\eta K\neq \eta$ in general), except if H (resp.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] K ) is the identity functor of the category D (resp.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If C is any category and I is a small category, we can form the functor category $C^{I}$ having as objects all functors from I to C and as morphisms the natural transformations between those functors.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This forms a category since for any functor F there is an identity natural transformation $1_{F}:F\to F$ (which assigns to every object X the identity morphism on $F(X)$ ) and the composition of two natural transformations (the "vertical composition" above) is again a natural transformation.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The isomorphisms in $C^{I}$ are precisely the natural isomorphisms.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] That is, a natural transformation $\eta :F\to G$ is a natural isomorphism if and only if there exists a natural transformation $\epsilon :G\to F$ such that $\eta \epsilon =1_{G}$ and $\epsilon \eta =1_{F}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The functor category $C^{I}$ is especially useful if I arises from a directed graph.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The horizontal and vertical compositions are the compositions between natural transformations described previously.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] A functor category $C^{I}$ is then simply a hom-category in this category (smallness issues aside).
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Every limit and colimit provides an example for a simple natural transformation, as a cone amounts to a natural transformation with the diagonal functor as domain.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Indeed, if limits and colimits are defined directly in terms of their universal property, they are universal morphisms in a functor category.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] If X is an object of a locally small category C , then the assignment $Y\mapsto {\text{Hom}}_{C}(X,Y)$ defines a covariant functor $F_{X}:C\to {\textbf {Set}}$ .
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] This functor is called *representable* (more generally, a representable functor is any functor naturally isomorphic to this functor for an appropriate choice of X ).
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The natural transformations from a representable functor to an arbitrary functor $F:C\to {\textbf {Set}}$ are completely known and easy to describe; this is the content of the Yoneda lemma.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The reason for Mac Lane's comment is that the study of functors is itself not complete without the study of natural transformations.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] The context of Mac Lane's remark was the axiomatic theory of homology.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] Different ways of constructing homology could be shown to coincide: for example in the case of a simplicial complex the groups defined directly (simplicial homology) would be isomorphic to those of the singular theory.
[src:monad-transformers/natural-transformation] What cannot easily be expressed without the language of natural transformations is how homology groups are compatible with morphisms between objects, and how two equivalent homology theories not only have the same homology groups, but also the same morphisms between those groups.
